We did some data cleaning at this stage and also created new dataframes to calculate data we were interested in.

  • converted date columns to datetime
  • calculated the duration in days
  • Averaged the duration of every event by event type
  • Looked at the top requestors by parks
  • Looked at the top requestor by event type and grouped by organization
  • Looked at which park has the most approved events
  • Looked at which parks were used the most by seasons(categorized months into each season)
In [823]:
import pandas as pd
# Convert the date columns to datetime
df['reservation_start_date'] = pd.to_datetime(df['reservation_start_date'])
df['reservation_end_date'] = pd.to_datetime(df['reservation_end_date'])

# Calculate the duration in days
df['duration'] = (df['reservation_end_date'] - df['reservation_start_date']).dt.total_seconds() / 3600 / 24

# 1. Average duration of every event by event type
average_duration_by_event_type = df.groupby('event_type')['duration'].mean()

# 2. Top requestors by parks
top_requestors_by_parks = df.groupby('park_facility_name')['requestor_'].value_counts().groupby(level=0).head(1)

# 3. Top requestor by event type and group by organization
top_requestor_by_event_and_org = df.groupby(['event_type','organization'])['requestor_'].value_counts().groupby(level=[0, 1]).head(1)

# 4. Which park has most approved events
most_approved_parks = df[df['permit_status'] == 'Approved'].groupby('park_facility_name').size().idxmax()

# 5. Top parks used by months categorized into seasons
df['month'] = df['reservation_start_date'].dt.month
seasons = {12: 'Winter', 1: 'Winter', 2: 'Winter', 3: 'Spring', 4: 'Spring', 5:'Spring', 6: 'Summer', 7: 'Summer', 8: 'Summer', 9: 'Fall', 10: 'Fall', 11:'Fall'}
df['season'] = df['month'].map(seasons)
top_parks_by_season = df.groupby('season')['park_facility_name'].value_counts().groupby(level=0).head(1)
# Output results
print("Average duration by event type:\n", average_duration_by_event_type)
print("\nTop requestors by parks:\n", top_requestors_by_parks)
print("\nTop requestor by event type and organization:\n",top_requestor_by_event_and_org)
print("\nPark with most approved events:", most_approved_parks)
print("\nTop parks used by season:\n", top_parks_by_season)

In [829]:
import numpy as np
top_requestor_by_event_and_org_df = top_requestor_by_event_and_org.reset_index(name='Count')
event_types = top_requestor_by_event_and_org_df['event_type'].unique()
organizations = top_requestor_by_event_and_org_df['organization'].unique()
# Create a list of colors for each organization
colors = ['skyblue', 'orange', 'green', 'red', 'purple', 'brown', 'pink','gray']
# Plotting the grouped bar chart
bar_width = 0.35 # Width of each bar
index = np.arange(len(event_types)) # Index for x-axis ticks
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 8))
# Plot each organization's count for each event type
for i, org in enumerate(organizations):
    org_data = top_requestor_by_event_and_org_df[top_requestor_by_event_and_org_df['organization']==org]
    counts = org_data['Count']
    plt.bar(index + i * bar_width, counts, bar_width, color=colors[i],label=org)
plt.xlabel('Event Type')
plt.ylabel('Number of Requests')
plt.title('Top Requestor by Event Type and Organization')
plt.xticks(index + bar_width / 2, event_types, rotation=90) # Label each event type on x-axis
plt.legend()

Here we will create a copy of the original datafram for EDA. We have converted the reservation start data and end date to the datetime form. Additionally we handled missing values by filling with them a placeholder(-1) so that instead of dropping the values we just filter them out.

In [831]:
import requests
url = 'https://data.cityofchicago.org/resource/pk66-w54g.json?$limit=125000'
r = requests.get(url)
print(f"Status code: {r.status_code}")
response_dict = r.json()
import pandas as pd
data = pd.DataFrame(response_dict)
data_copy = data.copy()
data_copy.head()
data_copy['reservation_start_date'] = pd.to_datetime(data_copy['reservation_start_date'])
data_copy['reservation_end_date'] = pd.to_datetime(data_copy['reservation_end_date'])
data_copy['reservation_start_date']
data_copy['reservation_end_date']
## Handling missing values
data_copy['park_number'] = data_copy['park_number'].fillna(-1)
print(data_copy['park_number'] == -1)

### Events per year
data_copy['Year'] = data_copy['reservation_start_date'].dt.year
events_per_year = data_copy['Year'].value_counts().sort_index()
data_copy['event_type'] = data_copy['event_type'].replace({'Permit - Event 6/10,000+':'Event 6'})
data_copy['event_type'] = data_copy['event_type'].replace({'Permit - Festival/Performance/12,001+ Event':'Festival/Performance Event'})
data_copy['event_type'] = data_copy['event_type'].replace({'Permit - Parking Lot Rental':'Parking Lot Rental Permit'})
data_copy['event_type'] = data_copy['event_type'].replace({'Permit - Promotions':'Promotional Event'})
mappings = {
'Administrative Reservation':'Administrative Reservation',
'Commemorative':'Commemorative',
'Athletic':'Athletic',
'Corporate Event':'Corporate Event',
'Media':'Media',
'Picnic':'Picnic',
'Venue Rental':'Venue Rental',
'Event 1 Cluster':'Event 1',
'Event 2 Cluster':'Event 2',
'Event 3 Cluster':'Event 3',
'Event 4 Cluster':'Event 4',
'Event 5 Cluster':'Event 5'
}
def categorize_event(event_description):
    for key,values in mappings.items():
        if key in event_description:
            return values
    return event_description
data_copy['Event Type Category'] = data_copy['event_type'].apply(categorize_event)
print(data_copy['Event Type Category'].unique())

    if month in [12, 1, 2]:
        return 'Winter'
    elif month in [3, 4, 5]:
        return 'Spring'
    elif month in [6, 7, 8]:
        return 'Summer'
    elif month in [9, 10, 11]:
        return 'Fall'

In [839]:
import matplotlib.colors as mcolors
data_copy['Month'] = data_copy['reservation_start_date'].dt.month
# Function to categorize months into seasons
def get_season(month):
    if month in [12, 1, 2]:
        return 'Winter'
    elif month in [3, 4, 5]:
        return 'Spring'
    elif month in [6, 7, 8]:
        return 'Summer'
    elif month in [9, 10, 11]:
        return 'Fall'
data_copy['Season'] = data_copy['Month'].apply(get_season)
heatmap_data = data_copy.pivot_table(index='park_number', columns='Season',values='reservation_start_date', aggfunc='count', fill_value=0)
total_reservations_per_park = data_copy.groupby('park_number')['reservation_start_date'].count()
top_parks = total_reservations_per_park.nlargest(10).index
filtered_heatmap_data = heatmap_data.loc[top_parks]

colors = ["lightgrey", "grey", "darkgrey", "#f71414"]
cmap = mcolors.LinearSegmentedColormap.from_list("custom_red_grey", colors,N=256)

plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
sns.heatmap(filtered_heatmap_data, annot=True, fmt="d", cmap=cmap, linewidths=.5)
plt.title('Top 10 Parks: Reservations by Season')
plt.xlabel('Season')
plt.ylabel('Park Number')
plt.show()

data_copy['reservation_start_date']
data_copy['reservation_end_date']
## Handling missing values
data_copy['park_number'] = data_copy['park_number'].fillna(-1)


### Events per year
data_copy['Year'] = data_copy['reservation_start_date'].dt.year
events_per_year = data_copy['Year'].value_counts().sort_index()
data_copy['event_type'] = data_copy['event_type'].replace({'Permit - Event 6/10,000+':'Event 6'})
data_copy['event_type'] = data_copy['event_type'].replace({'Permit - Festival/Performance/12,001+ Event':'Festival/Performance Event'})
data_copy['event_type'] = data_copy['event_type'].replace({'Permit - Parking Lot Rental':'Parking Lot Rental Permit'})
data_copy['event_type'] = data_copy['event_type'].replace({'Permit - Promotions':'Promotional Event'})
mappings = {
'Administrative Reservation':'Administrative Reservation',
'Commemorative':'Commemorative',
'Athletic':'Athletic',
'Corporate Event':'Corporate Event',
'Media':'Media',
'Picnic':'Picnic',
'Venue Rental':'Venue Rental',
'Event 1 Cluster':'Event 1',
'Event 2 Cluster':'Event 2',
'Event 3 Cluster':'Event 3',
'Event 4 Cluster':'Event 4',
'Event 5 Cluster':'Event 5'
}
def categorize_event(event_description):
    for key,values in mappings.items():
        if key in event_description:
            return values
    return event_description
data_copy['Event Type Category'] = data_copy['event_type'].apply(categorize_event)


mappings = {
'Approved':'Approved',
'Completed':'Approved',
'Issued':'Approved'
}
def status_change(permit_status):
    for key,values in mappings.items():
        if key in permit_status:
            return values
    return permit_status
data_copy['permit_status'] = data_copy['permit_status'].apply(status_change)

# Function to categorize months into seasons
def get_season(month):
    if month in [12, 1, 2]:
        return 'Winter'
    elif month in [3, 4, 5]:
        return 'Spring'
    elif month in [6, 7, 8]:
        return 'Summer'
    elif month in [9, 10, 11]:
        return 'Fall'

approved_events['Season'] = approved_events['Month'].apply(get_season)
heatmap_data = approved_events.pivot_table(index='park_number', columns='Season', values='reservation_start_date', aggfunc='count', fill_value=0)

def update_line_chart(year):
    # Resetting axes scales for consistent updates
    global x_sc, x_ax
    if year != 'All Years':
        monthly_data = approved_events[approved_events['Year'] == int(year)].groupby('Month_Name')['reservation_start_date'].count().reindex(['Jan', 'Feb', 'Mar', 'Apr', 'May', 'Jun', 'Jul', 'Aug', 'Sep', 'Oct', 'Nov', 'Dec'], fill_value=0)
    else:
        yearly_data = approved_events.groupby('Year')['reservation_start_date'].count()

    with line_chart_output:
        line_chart_output.clear_output(wait=True)
        if year != 'All Years':
            line.x = monthly_data.index
            line.y = monthly_data.values
            scatter.x = monthly_data.index
            scatter.y = monthly_data.values
            x_ax.label = 'Month'
        else:
            line.x = yearly_data.index
            line.y = yearly_data.values
            scatter.x = yearly_data.index
            scatter.y = yearly_data.values
            x_ax.label = 'Year'
        
        x_sc = OrdinalScale()
        fig.axes = [x_ax, y_ax]
#         plt.figure(figsize=(5, 3))
        display(fig)

Update Heatmap Function¶

In [858]:
def update_heatmap(year):
    # Filtering the data for the selected year or use all data if 'All Years' is selected
    filtered_data = approved_events[approved_events['Year'] == int(year)] if year != 'All Years' else approved_events
    
    # Creating a pivot table for the heatmap data
    heatmap_data = filtered_data.pivot_table(index='park_number', columns='Season', values='reservation_start_date', aggfunc='count', fill_value=0)

    # Calculating the total reservations for each park and get the top 10 parks
    total_reservations = heatmap_data.sum(axis=1).nlargest(10)
    top_parks = total_reservations.index

    # Filtering the heatmap data to include only the top 10 parks
    heatmap_data = heatmap_data.loc[top_parks]

    # Ensuring you have a dictionary or a way to map park numbers to names
    # If 'park_facility_name' is a column in 'filtered_data', create a mapping dictionary
    park_names = pd.Series(filtered_data['park_facility_name'].values, index=filtered_data['park_number']).to_dict()

    # Replacing park numbers with names in the index of heatmap data
    heatmap_data.index = heatmap_data.index.map(lambda x: park_names.get(x, 'Unknown'))

    with heatmap_output:
        heatmap_output.clear_output(wait=True)
        plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
        ax = sns.heatmap(heatmap_data, annot=True, fmt="d", cmap="coolwarm")
        plt.title('Top 10 Parks: Reservations by Season')
        plt.xlabel('Season')
        plt.ylabel('Park Name')
        ax.set_yticklabels(ax.get_yticklabels(), rotation=0)  # Make sure park names are readable
        plt.show()

def update_bar_chart(year):
    if year != 'All Years':
        filtered_data = approved_events[approved_events['Year'] == int(year)]
    else:
        filtered_data = approved_events
    top_parks = filtered_data['park_number'].value_counts().nlargest(5).index
    top_parks_data = filtered_data[filtered_data['park_number'].isin(top_parks)]
    top_requestors = top_parks_data.groupby(['park_number', 'requestor_']).size().reset_index(name='counts')
    top_requestors = top_requestors.sort_values(by=['park_number', 'counts'],ascending=[True, False])    
    top_requestors_by_park = top_parks_data.groupby(['park_number', 'requestor_']).size().reset_index(name='counts')
    total_reservations_by_requestor = top_requestors_by_park.groupby('requestor_').sum('counts').nlargest(10, 'counts')
    top_requestors_filtered = top_requestors_by_park[top_requestors_by_park['requestor_'].isin(total_reservations_by_requestor.index)]
    top_requestors_filtered = top_requestors_filtered.sort_values(by=['counts'],ascending=False)


    with bar_output:
        bar_output.clear_output(wait=True)
        colors = ["#f71414", "gray", "lightgray"]
        cmap = mcolors.LinearSegmentedColormap.from_list("custom_red_grey", colors, N=100)
        plt.figure(figsize=(10, 4))
        sns.barplot(x='counts', y='requestor_', hue='park_number', data=top_requestors_filtered, dodge=False,
                    palette=[cmap(i / float(len(top_parks))) for i in range(len(top_parks))],
                    linewidth=1, saturation=1, alpha=1, ci=None, orient='h', capsize=0, errwidth=0)
        plt.legend(title='Park Number', bbox_to_anchor=(1.05, 1), loc='upper left')
        plt.title('Top 10 Requestors with Park Number (Approved Events Only)')
        plt.xlabel('Number of Reservations')
        plt.ylabel('Requestor Name')
        plt.tight_layout()
        plt.show()

def update_donut_chart(year):
    if year != 'All Years':
        filtered_data = approved_events[approved_events['Year'] == int(year)]
    else:
        filtered_data = approved_events

    season_data = filtered_data.groupby('Season')['reservation_start_date'].count()
    colors = ["lightgrey", "darkgrey", "#f71414", "grey"]
    cmap = mcolors.LinearSegmentedColormap.from_list("custom_red_grey", colors, N=256)

    with donut_output:
        donut_output.clear_output(wait=True)
        # Adjust figsize to desired pixel dimensions divided by DPI (assuming 100 dpi)
#         fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(10, 10))  # 200px/100dpi by 100px/100dpi
        outer_circle = ax.pie(season_data, labels=season_data.index, autopct='%1.1f%%', startangle=90, colors=colors, wedgeprops=dict(width=0.2, edgecolor='w'))
        inner_circle = ax.pie([1], radius=0.3, colors=['white']) 

        ax.set_aspect('equal')
        ax.set_title('Total Reservations by Season')
        plt.show()

Prose:¶

  • One paragraph explaining how to use the dashboard you created, to help someone who is not an expert understand your dataset.
  • A list of 1 or more contextual datasets you have identified, links to where they reside, and a sentence about why they might be useful in telling the final story.
    • by "contextual dataset" here means a dataset that would add context to your chosen dataset. For example, if your dataset is the Champaign bus routes, some interesting contextual datasets could be the Chicago bus routes, or the Springfield bus routes, or the Amtrak routes in Champaign
    • you do not have to do anything with this dataset at the moment beyond writing a bit about why it would be useful. Looking forward, you will want to include "contextual visualizations" (which you may or may not generate on your own) in your Final Project, Part 3 and identifying a possibly useful dataset is a great way to start looking for contextual visualizations.
  • If you have identified your dataset as a "large one" (i.e. larger than the GitHub file upload limit) comment on if you want to revise your plan for hosting this data or not. If this does not apply to your dataset please explicitly state this.
  • Additionally, please note that as of writing, it is not possible to embed images within Starboard. Be sure to address how you plan on including your contextual dataset to add context to your main dataset given that you won't be able to directly embed images if you plan on using Starboard for Part 3.1 of the Final Project.
